{"/service/ndnp/gu/batch_gu_lassiter_ver01/data/sn90052143/00414182719/1913062101/0455.xml":{"full_text":"VOL. XII, MO. 202.\nBOARD OF TRADE\nSTARTS aMPAIGM\nFOR COL KINGMAN\nWILL BE RANKING COLONEL\nWHEN GEN. BIXBY IS RE\nTIRED DECEMBER 27.\nIN LINE FOR CHIEF ENGINEER\nNever Hat th* South Had the Oppor\ntunity t>l Backing a Man for This\nPosition Who la So Familiar With\nConditions in This Section.\nThe Brunswick Board of Trade\nhas started a campaign to have Col.\nDan C. Kingman succeed to the post\nof chief engineer, U. S. A, upon the\nretirement of Gen. Bixby on Dec. 27.\nTho Board of Trade has taken this\naction upon their own initiative, as\nthey don\u2019t even know that Col. King\nman cares for the position, ibut they\nbelieve that with his knowledge of\nconditions down here he is the right\nman for the place and are going to\nback him whether or no. Secretary\nWeatherly has communicated with\ntrade organizations throughout Use\nSouth and there is no question but\nthat Col. Kingman will have their\nunanimous endorsement at the prop\ner time, as recognition in, part of\nhis work and efforts on behalf of the\nSouth during his many years\u2019 service\nin this section.\nNever has this portion of the coun\ntry had the opportunity of placing in\nthis position, namely, chief of engi\nneers, a man so thoroughly familiar\nwith the needs of this section of the\nUnited States, and it is surely oppor\ntune for the trade organizations to\nunite In supporting Col. Kingman for\nthe position to which he is not only\nentitled as ranking officer, but for\nWhigb he is eminently, fitted.\nCW. Dan <C. Kingman was born\nMatch 6, 1852; educated at West\nPoint with later post-graduate work\nat Willett's Point and West Point;\none of his first assignments was at\nHellowettme park, the general plan of\nimprovement of which was initiated\nand Commenced by him; about 1890\none of his important posts was at\nNew Orleans, where he rendered sig\nnal Service in a fight against the 1890\nflood, and was tendered a vote of\nthanks by the senate and house of\nrepresentatives of the state of Lou\nisiana; later he was transferred to\nOswego, N. Y, following which he\nwas in charge of the improvements\nof the Tennessee river system at\nChattanooga, Tenn, his improvement\npf which has been adopted as stand\nard,, work in the corps of engineers;\nfrom there he was transferred to\nCleveland, Ohio, In 1901 and exten\nsive, harbor improvements carried on\nunder his direction. He was trans\nferred to Savannah in March, 1906,\nand made district engineer in charge\nof the southeast coast of the United\n\u2022J nc\u2014\u2014\nMUNICIPAL SALOON\nIS ESTABLISHED\n\u25a0BISSETiOiN, SOUTH .DAKOTA, WILL\nGET THE PROFITS OF THE\nBUSINESS.\nSisseton, S. D, June 20. \u2014Commenc-\ning July 1, Sisseton will have the\nnearest approach to a municipal sa\nloon of any town in .South Dakota.\nThe license for two saloons to which\nthe town is entitled were granted\nto W. E. Bollenbeck by popular vote.\nBolienbeck will conduct the busi\nness on unique lines. He will work\non a salary of SI,BOO a year and the\nprofits of his business will be divid\ned as follows:\nFifty per cent to the county good\nroads fund and the remaining 50 per\ncent to the city treasury.\nThe daily receipts of the saloon\nwill be turned over to two leading\ncitizens under whose control the bus\niness will be conducted. The name\nof the city will not appear in any of\nthe -transactions ot the saloon.\n\n81LK BTRIKERS SENTENCED.\nPatterson, June 20.\u2014Thirty-one\nstriking silk mill workers, members\nof the Industrial Workers of the\nWorld, convicted recently of unlawful\nassemblage, were sentenced today to\nserve three months each in jail. The\ncourt suspended sentence, subject to\nfood behavior of the prisoners.\nTHE BRUNSWICK NEWS.\nJAS. S. 6RAILEY, JR.,\nOPTIMISTIC OVER\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nt\nIMPROVEMENTS AND ADIDTIONS\nARE BEING MADE AT THE\nYARYAN PLANT.\nSALES EXCEED PRODUCTION\nAt a Meeting of the Receivers, Held\nYesterday, Officers Were Named\nfor the Plant in This City and at:\nGulfport as Well.\nJames S. Brailey, Jr., president of\nthe Yaryan Naval Stores company,\nwho has been in the city the past\nweek on business connected with the\nplant, left last night for his home in\nToledo, Ohio.\nWhen asked it{ aiding the rumors\nthat have been pi. sistently circulat\ned during the past week that the\n5 aryan plant in this city was to\nclose down Mr Hwtiley stated, em\nphatically, that there was absolutely\nno truth in the statement and that\non the contrary the affairs of the\n5 aryan company were in good shape\nnow, that improvements and additions\nto the plant were being made and\nthat for the past six weekg the sales\nhad exceeded the production 25 per\ncent \u2014facts that should put at rest\nany rumors of suspension.\nFollowing the failure of the Amer-\nI lean Naval Stores company conditions\nwere bad everywhere, the market be\ning paralyzed, but the recovery has\nbeen complete. The statement ot\nSecretary of the Treasury McAdoo\nthat he is prepared to place $500,-\n000,000 among the banks of the\ncountry has also done much to re\nlieve the tension.\nMr. Brailey was exceedingly opti\nmistic over the business outlook ger.\nerally and especially as regards\nBrunswick and the Yaryan Naval\nStores company.\nAt a meeting of the receivers of\nthe plant, James S. Brailey, Jr., Ho\nmer T. Yaryan and E. W. Stetson,\nheld yesterday, the following officers\nwere named to assume charge of\ntheir plants at Brunswick and at\nGulfport, Miss.:\nG. C. Smith, general manager.\nBrunswick Plant.\nJos. E. Lockwood, sales manager;\nH. W. Perry, plant manager; R. A.\nSanzenbacher, treasurer; C. E. Kin\nney', chemist.\nGulfport Plant.\nA. E. Fowle, plant manager; S. Y.\nBrigham, assistant treasurer; L. G.\nAndrews, cashier.\nin connection with the election of\nofficers, as given above, it will be\nnoted that G. C. Smith was elected\nto the position of general manager.\nHeretofore there has been no gener\nal manager of the combined plants,\nthe position having been created at\nthe meeting -yesterday. Mr. Smitli\nwas formerly assistant manager of\nthe local plant, and his promotion\nis a well merited one, as he has made\nthe company a most efficient, official.\nHe will maintain his headquarters in\nBrunswick, but will visit the Gulfport\nplant frequently.\nNEGROES ELECTROCUTED IN\nKENTUCKY FOR A MURDER\nEddyville, Ky\u201e June 20.\u2014(Condemn\ned for the murder of Hardin In\ngraham in Shelby county two years\nago, Tom Lawson and Tom Martin,\nnegroes, were electrocvuted in the\nstate penitentiary here today.\nIngraham was killed near the vil\nlage of Waddy after a young negro\ngirl had complained to a kinsamn\nthat she had been knocked from the\nsidewalk while passing a group of\nyoung white men.\nIt was charged that Lawson and\nMartin followed Ingraham from the\nvillage and killed him,\nMANSLAUGHTER VERDICT FOR\nAUTO KILLING AFFIRMED\nTrenton, N. J., June 20. \u2014.The su\npreme court today affirmed the cqp\nviction of Daniel A. Dugan, Jr., of\nmanslaughter. While driving his au\ntomobile on Christmas day, 1911, Du\ngan ran down and killed Leo Mc-\nDermott, a boy. Dugan\u2019s sentence of\nimprisonment at hard labor for not\nmore than ten nor less than five\nyears stands unless there is an ap\npeal to the court of errors and ap\npeals.\nDugan is a son of Judge Daniel A.\nDugan, of the Orange district court,\na personal friend of President Wilson\nwho appointed him to a judgeship\nabout a year ago.\nBRUNSWICK, GA\u201e SATURDAY M ORNING. JUNE 21, 1913.\nI r~ .j\n\n1\nTHE HON. W. G. BRANTLEY. V y|\nTo Receive Silver Service as Token of Appreciation.\nWILL PRESENT\nSILVER SERVICE\nv\nHANDSOME TESTIMONIAL TO\nBE GIVEN THE HON. W. G.\nBRANTLEY.\nThe committee having in charge\nthe testimonial to be presented to\ntile Hon. W. G. Brantley had a spe\ncial call meeting at the office of Al\nbert! Feiulig yesterday noon. The tes\ntimonial which will be in the form\nof a silver service to cost not less\nthan SSOO, will be given Mr. Brant\nley as a, mark of the high esteem in\nwhich lie is held by all Brunswick\nian3 and us a mark of appreciation of\nhis long and distinguished service in\ntile halls of congress.\nThe original idea was to limit the\ncontributions to one dollar, but the\ncommittee has decided to accept\nsums in any amount for the future.\nThe committee composed of F. D.\nAiken, chairman; Geo. H. Smith,\ntreasurer; Maj. Downing, Albert\nFendig, .1. W. Bennett, TI. F. Dun\nwody, D. 1). Atkinson, F. D. M.\nStrachao, .1. B. Wright and C. It.\nHeavy will at another meeting in\nthe near future, decide upon a date\nfor the presentation. Those desiring\nto participate in tlie testimonial may\nsend their contributions to Geo. H.\nSmitli, treasurer of committee, at the\nBrunswick Bank Trust Cos.\nWANT OLD \u00dcBERTY\nBELL SENT WEST\nTO GIVE SCHOOL CHILDREN A\nCHANCE TO SEE THE FA\nMOUS REiLIC.\nPhiladelphia, June 20.\u2014Pleading\nthat the school children of the West\nshould lie given an opportunity of\nseeing the Liberty Bell, nine young\nwomen teachers from Oregon, Wash\nington and Idaho called on Mayor\nBlankenberg and city council in an\neffort to secure the transportation of\nthe relic to the Panama-Pacific ex\nposition in 1915:\nMayor Blankenberg informed them\nthat he favored the sending of the\nbell, but said the question would have\nto be decided by members of council,\nto be elected next fall.\nPetitions signed by thousands of\nschool children and by the governors\nof tlie slates represented by the dele\ngation were presented to the council,\nthe members of which heartily ap\nplauded the speeches of the fair\npleaders, but failed to take any ac\ntion.\n\nFIGHTS OF A DAY.\nSan Francisco, June 20. \u2014Ad Wol\ngast and Red Watson, a California\nlightweight, are matched to fight\nhere tonight before the San Francis\nco Athletic club. The weight is 132\npounds ringside.\nTO CONFER OVER\nPITER AFFAIRS\nFAMILY HAS UNTIL WEDNESDAY\nTO ANSWER VITALS RE\nCEIVERSHIP SUIT.\n\nBaltimore, June 20.\u2014A. L. Jack\nson, attorney, left for Jacksonville\nearly this morning to confer with tin*\nwidow nnd daughter of E, Painter,\ntlie wealthy fertilizer manufacturer,\nfor whose vital organs the court lias\nbeen asked to appoint a receiver. Mr.\nJackson was accompanied by former\nJudge .1. A. Stewart, of DeLand, who\ncame to Baltimore to represent the\nPainter family in the litigation over\nthe insurance.\nTlie Painter family has been given\nby Judge Duffy until next Wednesday\nto show cause why u receiver should\nnot be appointed for Mr. Painter\u2019s or\ngans, or that part of them still in pos\nsession of Dr. (llasser, the chemist\nwho was employed by the family and\ninsurance company to make an analy\ntical examination.\nThe receivership was asked by the\nUnited States Fidelity Guaranty\nCos., which issued a $20,00(1 accident\npolicy on Mr. Painter\u2019s life. The com\npany alleged that physicians repre\nsenting the Painter family have al\nready gotten possession of part of\ntlie organs. Tlie court lias enjoined\nDr. Glasser from delivering tlie parts\nthat remain in his custody to anyone.\nIMMENSE PRIZES\nAT HORSE SHOW\nDISAPPOINTMENT OVER FACT\nTHAT AMERICA HAS NO RID\nING TEAM ENTERED.\nLondon, June 20. \u2014The internation\nal horse show, which opened here\nyesterday, to continue until June 30,\nis sure to be a brilliant success. The\nmanagement lias spent $250,000 on\nthe exhibition, offering $60,000 in\nprizes, a total greater than ever be\nfore.\nTlie decoration scheme is the most\nelaborate. It is modern ami floral In\ncolor and harmony. There is a se\nries of trellises, festooned with roses\ninclosing an enormous dark-green\nshell with a background lighted by\nthousands of invisible incandescents.\nIn tlie center of the festoons are gold\nvases of roses lighted from within.\nBelow surrounding the arena, is an\nAdam style border In gold, the coping\nis hung witli roses. Dozens of chande\nliers, also in the Adam style, are fes\ntooned with roses.\nThere is disappointment that an\nAmerican riding team is not entered\nin tlie competition for the King Ed\nward cup against the Russians, the\npresent holders. There are French,\nBelgians, Italians, Swedes and Brit\nish. But the American harness en\ntries are strong, and It Is believed\nthat they will take the blue ribbon\nM\u2019AOOO REARS\nHOW MARTIN WAS\nMADE J RESIGN\nPRESIDENT MAY CALL FLORIDA\nDELEGATION ON WHITE\nHOUSE CARPET.\nMARTIN WITHDRAWS LETTER\nThe Matter Has Been Called to the\nAttention of President Wilson, 1\nWho Is Indignant and May Call for\nan Investigation.\nWashington, June 20.\u2014a political\nscandal of no mean proportion ap\npears to he brewing within the Flori\nda delegation in congress, and some\nof its members may lie called upon\n\u2022he carpet by the president to explain\nwhy Collector of Customs J. W. Mar\ntin, of Jacksonville, whs compelled to\nsign a letter resigning the position ef\nfective on July I before the senate\nwould confirm the appointment. Sec\nretary McAdoo of tlie treasury depart\nment lias a letter from Martin giving\nm detail a narrative of tile events\nleading up to tlie forced resignation\nin advance, and tlie two Florida sen\nators have been asked to call and\nexplain.\nIt appears that Mr. Martin was ap\npointed collector of customs for the\ndistrict of Florida for a term of\nyears beginning May 31. Immediate\nly a clamor arose that the place was\nintended for someone else, seeing\nthat on July 1 tlie whole state of Flor\nida and a part of southern Georgia\nbecomes the district of Florida and\ntlie collector at Jacksonville automat\nically becomes collector for tlie en\nlarged job.\nAs It Is Played.\nMartin\u2019s nomination was sent to\n\u2022he senate and then withdrawn and\nMartin was summoned to Washing\nton, where, it is said, lie met Sona\nor Fletcher, who told him that ow\ning to opposition to giving Martin the\nlarger position having arisen he\nwould have to resign tlie commission\neffective July 1, or the senate would\nnot confirm him.\nMartin protested, it is announced,\nand called on Senator Bryan, who\n'.old him lie could do nothing and ad\nvised him to comply with the demand\nfor resignation. Martin returned to\nSenator Fletcher, who was inflexi\nble, so tlie story runs, and gave him\nthree days to decide upon his course.\nMartin consulted with friends, who\nadvised him to escape Hie humiliation\nof not being confirmed by a Demo\ncratic senate by agreeing to sign tlie\nletter. Then the tale runs, Martin re\nturned to tlie office of Senator Fletch\ner in the senate building and agreed\nlo Sign tlie letter.\nThe Narrative.\nSenator Fletcher, so (lie story goes,\ndictated tlie letter of resignation to\nliis stenographer, and had it tran\nscribed on a letterhead bearing tlie\nsenate mark and Ills name. Martin\nsigned tlie letter under protest, and\n-h it is alleged, Fletcher said;\nYou will be confirmed on Monday,\u201d\nuul on Monday tlie senate confirmed\nlie nomination.\nMartin wrote to tlie secretary of\nthe treasury a full account, or these\n\u2022vents and it is understood that the\nletter lias been called to the atten\n'.ion of tlie president, who is indig\nlant. He also withdrew ids resig\nlation, notifying Senators Fletcher\nirid Bryan that lie would fight to re\ntain tlie office until tlie expiration\nif his commission.\n\nMANY NATIONS EXPECTED.\nPittsburg, June 2b. In tlie prelim\ninary announcement of tlie plans for\nlie great world\u2019s Christian citizen\nship congress to he held June 29 to\nInly 6, local leaders in the movement\ntald today that a score of foreign\nountries would lie represented. T'.:e\ntentative program shows many\nnoted foreign speakers on the pro\ngram, as well as many prominent\nAmericans.\nhonorH.\nAnew American competitor is\nMiss K. Van Claire, of Pittsburg. -Bhe\nlias obtained a crack harness hors\nThe \\Vhip, for SIO,OOO, from llarnell\nTubbs; also a hackney stallion, A\nOne Douglass, from Dr. Marry, for\nSO,OOO.\nJudge Moore, always the strongest\nAmerican competitor, has brought a\ngreater string than usual. Alfred G.\nVanderbilt Is not competing in har\nness. Cast year he shipped his en\ntire rejuvenated Newport stables.\nIteginald Vanderbilt has entries. It\nis believed that the'arena will show\na battle royal among Americans.\nCURRENCY RILL\nWAS DISCUSSED\nBY CONGRESS\nDEMOCRATIC LEADERS GETTING\nMEASURE READY FOR\nINTRODUCTION.\nTO CHECK RESERVE RANKS\nUnderlying Idea Is to Effect An Easy\nChange From the Present Banking\nSystem By Using the Existing Ma\nchinery.\nWashington, June 20 ('ongress\nturned its eyes away from tlie tariff\ntoday and scrutinized the adminlstra\nion's currency hill.\nWhile the measuie will not he in\ntroduced in noth houses until next\nweek, tlie tentative draft bn.it.\nabout informal discussion generally\nby which President Wilson and the\nDemocratic leaders hoped to develop\ncomplete harmony when tlie bill is\nlaunched.\nW hile it lias been known for some\ntime Unit framers of tlie measure\u2014\nSecretary McAdoo, Senator Owen,\nRepresentative Glass and tlie presi\ndent contemplated a system of jv\nregional reserve banks in districts\nwhose areas were not necessarily\nt qual geographically, hut followed the\nlines of trade and domestic commerce\ninterest centered today In the pow\ners cf supervision to be exercised\noy tlie federal eserve board of nine\nmembers over the reserve bunks.\nThough originally it was planned\nto give tlie lmnks representation cm\ntlie federal reserve board, it was ar\ngued that the banks practically would\nhave tiie entire management of the\nfederal reserve lmnks and that by\nplacing tlie board entirely in govern-,\nmental control, a check on the oper\nations or tlie reserve hanks might, he\n.Assured.\nWant Easy Change.\nThe underlying Idea or the hill In\nflic minds of the framers has been\nto effect an easy and uuembarrasslng\nchange from tlie present bunking\nsystem by using existing machinery.\nThe bill is expected to lie the sub\nject of liberal amendment. Provi\nsion for retirement of 2 per 4ient\nbonds by which $700,000,0tt0 of nation\nill hank notes now are secured, so\nas to provide against depreciation,!\nwill he one of the foremost problems.\nThe provision for note issue, tlie\nadministration hopes, will not be\nchanged, it Is said to lie tlie result\nof a cureful canvass not only of\nprominent bankers, but business men,\nwho thought it practical and sound.\nOperation of tlie plan Is explained\nIn this way:\nWhenever a state or national Dunk\ndesires to obtain currency, it applies\nfirst lo tlie federal reserve batik iu\nPs region, accompanying with its ap\nplication a tender of collateral secu\nrity. The security thus offered must\nbe notes and bills accepted for re\ndiscount under rules laid down by\ntlie federal reserve board, which may\nissue up to $500,000,000 111 notes.\nThe federal reserve hanks must hold\n33 13 per cent in gold of the amount\nof notes advanced. The notes also\nbecome a first and paramount lien on\nall tlie assets of the federal reserve\nbanks.\nAttention was centered today in\ntlie re-discounting feature as one of\ntlie fundamentals on whicli the entire\nplan is based. The power of the re\ngional reserve hank Is specifically\nbroadened to discount notes and bills\nof exchange arising out of connner- j\ncial transactions. It is tills itower.\nwhich, iu times of stress, admlnist.ra-J\ntlon officials think, will alleviate mon\ney strain.\nWhile tlie federal reserve hoard,\nthrough its agent in the federal re\nserve bank, would have the right to\ndetermine and define the character\nof the paper eligible for discount,\nthat definition will not include notes\nor hills drawn for the purpose of car\nrying or trading in stocks and bonds\nor other Investment securities, ex\ncept notes and hills having maturity\nof not exceeding four months and se\ncured by United States, state, county\nor municipal* bonds.\nFIRST REGIMENT BAND AT\nHANOVER PARK LAST NIGHT\nThe First Regiment band, which\nwill accompany the 'Brunswick Ri\nflemen to the summer camp on St.\nSimon, gave a very attractive pro\ngram of music at Hanover park last\nnight.\nThe hand has its full complement\nof musicians at present and is a\nsplendid organization, the concert\nwas much appreciated by those in\nattendance.\nIpil\n|\u00a9J\nprice five cents.\nSOLDIERS ARRIVE\nTHIS MORNING\nOVERJOUTHERN\nWILL INAUGURATE SITE FOR\nSUMMER CAMP ON ST.\nSIMON.\nBRUNSWICK RILFLEMEN TO 60\n4\nAccompanied By First Infantry Band\nThey Will Join \u00a3he Other Compa\nnies and Proceed to the Island for\nan Eight-Day Stay.\nThe Holi'.ier hoys of Hie Georgia na\ntional guard assigned to inaugurate\nHie summer camp on St. Simon will\narrive over the Southern railway at\n7 o\u2019clock tills morning. They will\ntransfer upon arrival to the steamers\nSea Gate and Atlantic, of the St. Si\nmon Transit company, for transpor\ntation to the island.\nFive troops of the Second squadron\ncavalry, dismounted, under command\nof .Ma.i, J. O. Seamans and including\nthe Georgia llussurs, of Savannah;\nthe Governor's Horse Guards, of At\nlanta, and the Liberty Independent\nTroop and the Third separate bat\ntalion under command of Ma.i. Hun\nter including the l.yndale guards and\nthe Winder and lClberton companies,\nwill make up the assignment to ar\nrive. They will be joined here by the\nBrunswick Riflemen, (\u2019apt. C. H. Tay\nlor, assigned temporarily to the Third\nbattalion.\nThe Riflemen will be accompanied\nby the First Infantry band and both\nwill go Into camp with a full roster\nof men.\nt'apt. .1. M. Kimbrough, IT. S. A.,\nwho Inspected the camp last\u201d WednCs\nlay, expresses himself as highly\npleased, not only with the location\nof the site, but with the facilities\nprovided, ('apt. Kimbrough has es\ntablished himself at the adjutant gen\neral's headquarters and will remain\nduring Hie full time of the encamp\nmenf\nAdjt.-Gen. Nasli will visit the camp\nthe coming week, by which time ev\nerything will be spick and spun for\nills inspection.\nThe adjutant general has stated on\nseveral occasions that lie looked upon\ntills camp as in the nature of an out\ning for (lie boys and that the hard\nroutine of camp lire would be done\naway with. Under these conditions\nthere is no question but what this\n\u2022summer will be long remembered b.*\nthe boys,\" especially from the Inte\nrior of the state.\n\u2019GETTE ESCAPES IN\nMEN\u2019S CLOTHING\nLILLIAN LENTON MAKEB HEM\nGETAWAY WHILE ON HUN\nGER STRIKE.\nLondon, June 2U. Miss Lillian\nLenton, the militant suffragette, who\nwas convicted of having started the\nfire in the Kow Tea Garden pavilion\nand who lias given the police much\ntrouble, has escaped in men\u2019s cloth\ning from flu house where she was\nliving in Leeds, pending the expira\ntion of her license.\nMiss Lenton was released from Jail\nIn March because of Illness, caused\nby a hunger strike. She broke her\nlicense and was not beard of again\nuntil June 10, when she was arrested\nat Doncaster under dramatic otreum\nstunces. A woman named Winshlp\nwas charged with breaking into West\nHeld house at Doncaster with the in\ntent to burn it.\nA witness for the defense who cali\n\"d herself May Dennis confessed that\nshe and not the Winshlp woman was\nguilty. She proved to be Miss Len\nton, for whom the police had been\nsearching. The Winshlp woman was\nreleased and Miss Lenton was sent\nback to jail.\nMiss Lenton immediately started\nanother hunger strike, and got out\non license a few days ago. She was\nthen placed in a house at Leeds un\ntil she had sufficiently recovered to\nlie returned to jail and police guard\ned the bouse. She again eluded the\npolice and got away yesterday.","height":"20112","width":"16116"}}
